<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">30052800</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2019</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>26</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2021</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>04</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1758-535X</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>74</Volume><Issue>4</Issue><PubDate><Year>2019</Year><Month>Mar</Month><Day>14</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>The journals of gerontology. Series A, Biological sciences and medical sciences</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Gerontol A Biol Sci Med Sci</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Resistance Training Alone or Combined With N-3 PUFA-Rich Diet in Older Women: Effects on Muscle Fiber Hypertrophy.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>489</StartPage><EndPage>494</EndPage><MedlinePgn>489-494</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1093/gerona/gly130</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>We aimed to examine cellular and molecular changes in skeletal muscle of recreationally active older women in response to 24 weeks of combined resistance training and N-3 PUFA-rich healthy diet. Sixty-three women (65-70 years) were randomized into resistance training and healthy diet rich in N-3PUFAs (RT-HD), resistance training only (RT) and controls (CON). Fiber type-specific morphological characteristics and gene expression of inflammatory biomarkers and regulators of muscle mass were analyzed in m. vastus lateralis biopsies obtained before the intervention and 4 days after the last training session. Gene expression of the proinflammatory cytokine IL-1&#x3b2; was downregulated (p &lt; .05) and that of the regulator of cellular growth mTOR (p &lt; 0.05) was upregulated in skeletal muscle of RT-HD only. There was also a significant hypertrophy of fast type IIA muscle fibers in RT-HD only (+23%, p &lt; .05). In conclusion, resistance training combined to an N-3 PUFA-rich healthy diet but not alone triggers local anti-inflammatory and growth responses, favoring skeletal muscle hypertrophy in already recreationally active older women.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; The Author(s) 2018. Published by Oxford University Press on behalf of The Gerontological Society of America. All rights reserved. For permissions, please e-mail: journals.permissions@oup.com.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Strandberg</LastName><ForeName>Emelie</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Health Sciences, &#xd6;rebro University, Sweden.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Ponsot</LastName><ForeName>Elodie</ForeName><Initials>E</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Health Sciences, &#xd6;rebro University, Sweden.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Piehl-Aulin</LastName><ForeName>Karin</ForeName><Initials>K</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Health Sciences, &#xd6;rebro University, Sweden.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Falk</LastName><ForeName>Gunnar</ForeName><Initials>G</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Health Sciences, &#xd6;rebro University, Sweden.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kadi</LastName><ForeName>Fawzi</ForeName><Initials>F</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>School of Health Sciences, &#xd6;rebro University, Sweden.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D003160">Comparative Study</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016449">Randomized Controlled Trial</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D013485">Research Support, Non-U.S. Gov't</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>United 